# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1871-boston-red-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The Cleveland Forest Citys played their first season in 1871 as a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] They finished eighth in the league with a record of 10–19.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Pitcher Al Pratt led the NA in strikeouts, with 34.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The honor of playing the first game of the newly organized National Association of Professional Baseball Players was decided by coin flip.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Bobby Mathews, 5 ft 5 in (1.65 m), 140 lbs, and 20 years old, hurled a 2-0 shutout for the Kekiongas.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Deacon White, catcher for the Cleveland Forest Citys got 3 hits in 4 at-bats; the other Cleveland players only shared 2 hits among them.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Deacon White scored the first hit, the first extra-base hit (a double) and was the first to hit into a double-play.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The game was rained out in the top of the 9th inning.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Bobby Mathews, who went on to play five seasons each in the National Association, National League, and American Association, is the only player ever to pitch 100 games or to win at least 50 in three different major leagues.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] He is credited with inventing the spitball and the out-curve.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Deacon White was another historic player, ending his 22-year career as playing owner of Buffalo's Brotherhood team.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-fort-wayne-kekiongas-season] The Fort Wayne Kekiongas played their first and only season in 1871 as a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-fort-wayne-kekiongas-season] They finished seventh in the league with a record of 7−12.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-fort-wayne-kekiongas-season] Bobby Mathews, 5 ft 5 in (1.65 m), 140 lbs, and 20 years old, hurled a 2−0 shutout for the Kekiongas.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-new-york-mutuals-season] The **New York Mutuals** baseball team (1857–1876) joined the National Association for the league's debut season in 1871.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-new-york-mutuals-season] The Mutuals went 16-17 and finished in fifth place.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-new-york-mutuals-season] Pitcher Rynie Wolters led the NA in runs batted in, with 44.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, the Athletic Baseball Club of Philadelphia was one of the first clubs to join.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics had been around since 1860 as an amateur club.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Led by their captain and pitcher, Dick McBride, the team went 21–7 and won the first NA title during the 1871 season.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia's third baseman, Levi Meyerle, led the league with a .492 batting average.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] The Rockford Forest Citys played their first and only season in 1871 as a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] They finished ninth in the league with a record of 4–21.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] Rockford finished with 4 wins and 21 losses, 15½ games behind the champion Philadelphia Athletics club and good for last place.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] Player-manager Scott Hastings was found to have violated the "60 day rule" implemented by the league—if a player switched teams during the season, the team had to bench him for 60 days before he could play.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] Hastings had jumped from a Louisiana team to the Forest Citys in the spring and immediately begun playing for Rockford.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] This complaint was brought before the league, and the Forest Citys were forced to forfeit 4 of their wins.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] The star of the team was Cap Anson, who hit .325 for the Forest Citys and would go on to become the player-manager of the Chicago White Stockings for over 20 seasons.
[src:1871-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-rockford-forest-citys-season] Anson was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1939.
